<dl id="n34068a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34068a">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34068a"> 68(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Sexagesima <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n34068a"><li>FW 298.27 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/lexlg.htm#n34068a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lg/l39lg.htm#n34068a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n34068a">MS BL 47478-60</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:138 <a name="lgd8" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lgd8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lg/lgd8.htm#n34068a">Draft: II.2&sect;8.8</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: LENT, in the Christian Church, the period of fasting preparatory to the festival of Easter. As this fast falls in the early part of the year, it became confused with the season, and gradually the word Lent, which originally meant spring, was confined to this use. The now superseded Latin name for the fast, <i>Quadragesima</i> is derived from the Sunday which was the fortieth day before Easter, as <i>Quinquagesima</i> and <mark>Sexagesima</mark> are the fiftieth and sixtieth, <i>Quadragesima</i> being until the 7th century the first day of the fast. </mm> </dd></dl>
